    "description": "The Salinae Herculeae, known from both epigraphic and literary testimony, were salt pans located in the vicinity of Pompeii and Herculaneum.",
    "details": "<p>Writing in Pauly-Wissowa, Hans Philipp describes <span>the<em> salinae </em>as</span> located between Torre del Greco and Torre del Annunziata. In a <em>titulus pictus </em>known from Pompeii (<em>CIL </em>IV, 128), one Marcus Cerinnius seeks electoral support for his campaign to become <em>aedile salinienses</em>. Another painted inscription (<em>CIL </em>IV, 1611) reads \"Salinesibvs feliciter\" and confirms indications that the salt pans lent their name to a district of Pompeii's <em>ager</em>. See <a class=\"external-link\" href=\"https://www.zotero.org/groups/2533/pleiades/items/ZGV3FQTX/library\" target=\"_self\" title=\"DeCarlo 2007\">DeCarlo 2007</a> note 2.</p>",
